			<common:generalComment xml:lang="en">Divalent mercury ions and compounds (Hg(II)) are found in various environments such as drinking water, natural surface water, seawater, wastewater, and aqueous soil extracts. They can be determined using a method called Anodic Stripping Voltammetry (ASV), as outlined in Method 7472. Mercury is a heavy, silvery-white metal that is liquid at room temperature and is a fair conductor of electricity.</common:generalComment>
